On Sun, 9 Oct 2005, Karl wrote:
>211 953 513 F  flashing indicator switch- Self  cancelling
>                         *to chassis 211 2114 988

I'd guess it starts wherever the parts book starts - assuming the parts
book has a start date on it.  Or, maybe when that parts book was
printed, that was the only switch still available for everything from
early '71 models back.

>211 953 513 H  flashing indicator switch- Self  cancelling
>                          *from 211 2114 989 to 211 2300 000

Like you said, late 1971 models.  Interestingly, this turns up in the
catalogs as fitting 73-ish models.

>211 953 513 J   flashing indicator switch- Self  cancelling
>                          [earlier non-US use snipped]
>                          *from 212 2000 001

Starting with the first 1972 models.  This also agrees with the catalogs
above.

>211 953 513 G  flashing indicator switch- Self  cancelling
>                          *to 219 300 000  with M-code M 524

To the end of the 1969 models.

>                          from 219 000 001 without emergency light system

Starting with the first 1969 models.  If it fits mechanically, there's
nothing weird about using this switch on a Bus with no hazard flashers.
On such a Bus, the wire from the brake light switch(es) would go
straight to terminal 54St (black/purple) on the switch.  On a Bus with
hazard flashers, the brake light switch wire goes through the hazard
flasher switch.

>                           from 210 2000 001 with buzzer for ignition- starter
>                           switch  211-265 models USA and Canada

Starting with the first 1970 models.  But the turn signal switch doesn't
have any contacts in it for the key buzzer - that's all in the ignition
switch.  Odd.

>                           from 212 2000 001 211-241 models USA, Canada

Starting with the first 1972 models.

I'm not 100% sure, but I think I agree that you want the G switch.

BTW, is this bay-window parts manual online somewhere?

